  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Buyer's guide</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">What to look for in <span class="accent">autoblogging software.</span></h2>
      <p>Five questions to ask before subscribing to any autoblogging software platform.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">01</span><div><h4>Does it publish to your CMS, or just generate a draft?</h4><p>Many tools called "autoblogging software" only generate a Word doc or HTML file. True autoblogging software pushes content to your CMS automatically. Confirm before subscribing.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">02</span><div><h4>Does it handle keyword research, or do you supply the keywords?</h4><p>Some platforms require you to upload a CSV of keywords. Others do the research automatically. The difference is hours of manual work per month.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">03</span><div><h4>Are there hidden per-article or credit-based charges?</h4><p>Calculate the true monthly cost by dividing total credits by credits per article. Many "$19/mo" plans produce fewer articles than advertised when you account for credit consumption.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">04</span><div><h4>Does it support your CMS?</h4><p>Seven of ten platforms only support WordPress. If you're on Webflow, Ghost, or Shopify, your options narrow to theStacc, Journalist AI, Byword, and Koala.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">05</span><div><h4>Does it include SEO optimization, or just content generation?</h4><p>Keyword insertion, schema markup, meta descriptions, internal linking, and featured image creation add up to 30+ minutes per article manually. Confirm which steps the software handles automatically.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
